				\begin{document}$$ \mathrm{PbIz}+\mathrm{CH}3\mathrm{NH}3\mathrm{I}\overset{70-80{}^{\circ}\mathrm{C}}{\to}\mathrm{C}\mathrm{H}3\mathrm{NH}3\mathrm{PbI}3. $$\end{document}

Increasing of the temperatures leads to the appearance of PbI2 peaks (2Θ = 12.8 °), which can be explained by the partial decomposition of the perovskite. It has been shown that other possible products of the decomposition of perovskite CH3NH3PbI3, except for the phase of PbI2, are CH3NH2 and HI [42, 43]. Authors [44] have been shown that in the Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) spectra of the products, there are bands indicating the presence of a C-I bond. Therefore, the reaction of the decomposition of organic-inorganic perovskite can be written as:2CH3NH3PbI3→>80°СPbI2+CH3I↑+NH3↑\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \mathrm{CH}3\mathrm{NH}3\mathrm{PbI}3\overset{>80{}^{\circ}\mathrm{C}}{\to}\mathrm{PbI}2+\mathrm{CH}3\mathrm{I}\uparrow +\mathrm{NH}3\uparrow $$\end{document}

For the systems, where the starting reagents were in the ratio PbI2:CH3NH3I = 1:2, after evaporation of the solvent, the formation of the additional phase (CH3NH3)2PbI4 has been observed (Fig. 4b). With the increasing of the temperature of heat treatment up to 180 °C, the decreasing of the intensity of this peak have been observed. At 180 °C, the resulting films were single-phase. The scheme of the reaction of formation of perovskite, where the starting reagents were taken in the ratios PbI2:CH3NH3I = 1:2, can be written as:PbI2+2CH3NH3I→20−120°CCH3NH32PbI4→>180°C\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
